<task id="005" project="agent-framework-fit-assessment-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Deployment model recommendations + aggregated migration cost analysis</title>
    <phase>4</phase>
    <tags>assessment, deployment, migration, adr-013, bff-extensions</tags>
    <estimate>1.5h</estimate>
    <status>completed</status>
    <completion-summary>Completed 2026-06-03 via sub-agent (commit 45b93668). Output: notes/05-deployment-and-migration.md (476 lines). Deployment models per ADOPT/PARTIAL: S1/S3/S5A/S8a/S8b in-process BFF (ADR-013 criteria 1+2 fail decisively for S1, criterion 4 fails for S3, S5A is wrapper-only); S5B all four ADR-013 §"Exceptions" criteria pass but three deployment candidates (Workflows-in-BFF · Workflows-in-Function · Foundry-hosted) cannot be ranked from current sources — **prototyping required before SPEC commitment, LOW confidence due to F12 evidence gap**; S7 deferred to D-A20 contract authoring. Publish-size: BASELINE 45.65 MB → worst-case 47-54 MB (well under 80 MB tolerance). Key finding: `Microsoft.Agents.AI 1.0.0-rc1` is already referenced in Sprk.Bff.Api.csproj lines 29-33, so S1/S3/S5A/S8a/S8b lifts have **net-zero publish-size impact**. Only S5B adds new packages (+1.5-6 MB cumulative, UNCERTAIN). 10 risks; 3 HIGH-severity: R1 (#6268 unresolved on S1 canonical workload), R2 (F12 durable-hosting evidence thin — pre-commitment is design-by-assumption), R9 (S5B mis-scoping as "framework adoption" rather than "build multi-day legal workflows from scratch"). Migration cost: 8-17 person-weeks for Phase 1+2+3 (Builder pre-work + shared infra middleware lift + per-surface S1-family lifts), excluding S5B (greenfield, person-quarters) and S7 (deferred). Confidence LOW-MED. F12 evidence gap forced explicit prototyping recommendation for S5B — "uncomfortable conclusions land better than premature confident ones."</completion-summary>
    <parallel-group>—</parallel-group>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
    <dependencies>004</dependencies>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    <goal>For surfaces with ADOPT or PARTIAL recommendations from task 004, produce: (a) explicit deployment-model recommendation keyed to ADR-013 + ADR-001 + bff-extensions.md, (b) aggregated migration cost + risk analysis. Output: projects/agent-framework-fit-assessment-r1/notes/05-deployment-and-migration.md. This feeds assessment doc §6 (deployment recommendations) and §7 (migration cost + risks).</goal>
    <context>Deployment is the question that turns "should we use Agent Framework" into "where exactly does it live." Per ADR-013, default is in-process BFF. Per SPEC §4d, exceptions require all four criteria + the agent-specific deployment options (in-process BFF / MCP server / Function / hosted Foundry Agent). For each adopt-surface, the assessment must commit to a model.</context>
    <constraints>
      - Skip surfaces with DON'T ADOPT recommendations from task 004 (note them as "no migration; no deployment change")
      - For each adopt-surface: explicit deployment model — one of (in-process BFF | MCP server | Azure Function | hosted Foundry Agent | mixed-with-specifics)
      - Cite ADR-013 §4 criteria explicitly when justifying a non-default deployment
      - Cite bff-extensions.md publish-size baseline (~60 MB compressed) when discussing package impact
      - Aggregate migration cost: total estimated dev effort (rough — person-weeks), risk areas (publish-size, OTel pipeline disruption, test infrastructure changes, team learning), reversibility per surface
      - Surface BFF publish-size risk explicitly if any adoption adds new top-level NuGet refs — bff-extensions.md says baseline is ~60 MB compressed; the BFF jumped to 75+ MB in 2026-05-19 from accumulated additions
      - If any deployment model is genuinely novel for Spaarke (e.g., hosting Agent Framework agents AS Foundry agents): flag it as needing prototyping, not direct adoption
    </constraints>
  </prompt>
